commits.author: Tomer Shmilovich
commits.message:
[Core] Support NIXL storage obj backend (#1557)

* [Core] Generalize NixlFilePool

Signed-off-by: Tomer Shmilovich <tshmilovich@nvidia.com>

* [Core] NixlStorageBackend support backend params

Signed-off-by: Tomer Shmilovich <tshmilovich@nvidia.com>

* [Core] Support NixlStorageBackend OBJ backend

Adding support for NIXL obj backend.

in order to use this backend, AWS parameters should be provided via
extra_config.nixl_backend_params in the yaml file, for example:

extra_config:
  enable_nixl_storage: true
  nixl_backend: OBJ
  nixl_pool_size: 64
  nixl_path: /mnt/nixl/cache/
  nixl_backend_params:
    access_key: <your_access_key>
    secret_key: <your_secret_key>
    bucket: <your_bucket>
    region: <your_region>

Signed-off-by: Tomer Shmilovich <tshmilovich@nvidia.com>

* [Docs] Update docs

Signed-off-by: Tomer Shmilovich <tshmilovich@nvidia.com>

commits.author: Martin Hickey
commits.message:
[Misc]: Improve the description provided for PRs (#1679)

Improve description provided for PRs

This commit updates the PR template so that it may guide users to
provide more details about the PR being submitted. At the moment, it is
usually just issue number that it fixes.

The value is twofold:

1. Its helps the reviewers understand what the PR does and if needed
2. It help others that find the PR later and understand the reason
behind the changes

It also moves details about identifier prefixes to the contributor guide
which is a more relevant place for them.

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

commits.message:
[BugFix][Testing]: Enable unit tests for GDS backend (#1648)

* Fix the GDS tests to work with the updated GdsBackend class constructor

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Fix unit test issues

This commit fixes the failing tests for the GDS backend.
It also checks for CUDA and Linux as these are backend
requirements.

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Fix GDS backend batched_submit_put_task method to return Futures

The GDS backend batched_submit_put_task method calls the submit_put_task
method to persist memory objects to the backend. The submit_put_task
uses a thread safe co-routine to call backend asynchronous persistence
method. This commit fixes batched_submit_put_task to return the Futures
objects from submit_put_task to the caller.

Unit test test_batched_submit_put_task was failing because the Future objects
were none.

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

commits.message:
[Test]: Enable unit tests to run on non-CUDA environment (#1575)

* Enable storage backend unit tests to run as non-CUDA

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Add pytest asyncio dependency for async tests

Tests in tests/v1/storage_backend/test_gds_backend.py were not
being run as they required async library.

This adds the pytest asyncio package which enabkles the tests to be run
by default rather than skipping them.

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Add unit test GitHub workflow for non-CUDA tests

This workflow will run non-CUDA unit tests which can run on the
standard runners which are not GPU enabled.

This could help catch issues prior to the running the full tests
on GPU systems. This could be helpful towards resource savings.

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Pinned memory does not work on non-CUDA systems

Pinned (pageâ€‘locked) memory is a CPUâ€‘side optimization for faster,
asynchronous transfers to a CUDA device. If thereâ€™s no CUDA context or
no allocator registered, PyTorch canâ€™t actually pin the memory, so it complains.

commits.message:
[Chore]: Remove Python 3.9 as the minimum Python version (#1618)

* Remove Python 3.9 as the minimum Python version

LMCache was built on Python 3.10 and as such has keywords like
match which are not compatible in Python 3.9. We therefore
would need to make changes to the code base. Python 3.9
will no longer be supported next month. Therefore, it is more
practical to support 3.10 as the minimum version.

This is a revert of some of the changes in:
https://github.com/LMCache/LMCache/pull/1440

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Changes required after code quality tools ran

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

commits.author: Isaac K. Ko
commits.message:
[Bugfix][Enhancement] Improve multi-round-qa.py and data_preprocessing.py scripts (#1321)

* multi-round-qa: fix argument name for init_logger

Using the --verbose option causes an error.

In the init_logger function, `level` should be changed to `log_level`,
or omit it as in this patch.

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* multi-round-qa: add an assert for insufficient trace data

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* multi-round-qa: add --dry-run option

This option helps quickly validate trace readability.

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* data_preprocessing: add --model option

This option allows you to specify a different tokenizer. The default
value is still `mistralai/Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.2`.

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* data_preprocessing: adjust estimate_num_tokens location

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* data_preprocessing: exclude invalid conversations

Although there has been some existing logic to exclude invalid
conversations, it is still insufficient.

This patch excludes the following invalid conversations:

- The number of conversations is not even
- The conversation starts with GPT or system
- The conversation ends with human
- GPT or human appears consecutively
- The conversation is too long (may exceed the maximum model length)
- Unknown "from" values

Experimental results using `ShareGPT_V3_unfiltered_cleaned_split.json`
are as follows:

  $ python data_preprocessing.py
  Number of IDs: 94145
  Excluded number of IDs: 58746
  Data to process: 35399

A significant number of traces are excluded.

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* data_preprocessing: use tqdm in loops

The script takes several minutes to run, so it's better to have a
progress bar.

  $ python data_preprocessing.py
  Loading trace file..
  Number of IDs: 94145
  Veryfing trace..
  100%|â–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆ| 94145/94145 [01:28<00:00, 1069.70it/s]
  Excluded Number of IDs: 58746
  Data to Process: 35399
  100%|â–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆ| 35399/35399 [01:06<00:00, 531.55it/s]

`tqdm` is already a dependency of `vLLM` and `LMCache`, so there's no
additional installation required.

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* data_preprocessing: add --trace option

This option allows you to specify a trace file. The default value is
still `ShareGPT_V3_unfiltered_cleaned_split.json`.

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* multi-round-qa: fix QPS print statement to print actual QPS value

The print statement outputs qps (configured value) but not _qps (actual
value):

  print(f"  \033[33mQPS: \033[32m{qps:.4f} reqs/s\033[0m\n")

Fix the print statement to output both configured value and actual value.

Changes:

- Rename config qps (`qps`) to `config_qps`
- Rename actual qps (`_qps`) to `actual_qps`
- Print both `actual_qps` and `config_qps`

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* doc: update README.md for multi-round-qa and data_preprocessing

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

---------

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

commits.author: Martin Hickey
commits.message:
[Refactor]: Remove duplicate requirements loading in setup tools (#1015)

Remove duplicate requirements loading in setup tools

RProject requirements are loaded from pyproject.toml since PR #728.
However, #702 was not rebased with changes and therefore
re-introduced the loading of project requirements again in setup tools.

This results in a warning message when install the project as follows:
/tmp/pip-build-env-3fib4lf4/overlay/lib/python3.12/site-packages/setuptools/config/_apply_pyprojecttoml.py:82:
SetuptoolsWarning: `install_requires` overwritten in `pyproject.toml` (dependencies)

This commit rollback the unnecessary duplication.

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

commits.author: Dan Aloni
commits.message:
[Feat] GdsBackend: allow to pass use_direct_io flag (#862)

GdsBackend: allow to pass use_direct_io flag

This flag allows to benchmark underlying file system performance with
respect to KV cache load/save. When it is being passed, and while cuFile
POSIX fallback is being used, the Linux pagecache does not cache the
file's content.

Signed-off-by: Dan Aloni <dan@kernelim.com>

commits.author: Dan Aloni
commits.message:
[Misc] GdsBackend: add internal fallback to POSIX APIs (#811)

* [Misc] GdsBackend: add internal fallback to POSIX APIs

In this change a `use_cufile` extra config variable is added to control
whether cuFile APIs will be used by GdsBackend. In addition, based on
fstype we can control the default vault of this variable and can turn
cuFile usage off.

The libcufile APIs are not always successful in implementing the POSIX
compatibility fallback. when either the cuFile own POSIX implementation
is triggered, or when GdsBackend's own POSIX implementation is used,
there expected to be at least one copy of data from main memory to GPU
buffers.

Fixes: #795

Signed-off-by: Dan Aloni <dan@kernelim.com>

* [Misc] GdsBackend: use_cufile - allow case insenstive "true" as input

Signed-off-by: Dan Aloni <dan@kernelim.com>

Signed-off-by: Dan Aloni <dan@kernelim.com>

commits.author: Ilya Yanok
commits.message:
Micro benchmark for VLLMPagedMemGPUConnectorV2.toGpu and a performance fix (#678)

* gpu_connector: add VLLMPagedConnectorV2.to_gpu micro-benchmark

We've noticed it spends a lot of time in
VLLMPagedConnectorV2._pointers_are_good, so before trying to improve it,
adding a micro-benchmark.

* pagedMemGPUConnectorV2: optimize to/from GPU

There was a number of issues with `_pointersAreGood` method, causing
it to massively dominate the to/from GPU cost.

First, why even check it, if the check takes linear time at worst, and
the initialization is also linear?

Then, getting/setting elements of a tensor is suboptimal, let's do it
in a single assignment instead.

And finally, the actual multi-layer transfer kernel runs on GPU, so
let's move pointers there.

This gives 3.3x speedup in the microbenchmark, see the results here:
https://gist.github.com/yanok/685182fe15b46bf0d99797853a4f9f9a

I only changed the VLLMPagedMemGPUConnectorV2 class, since that's the
one we are currently using in our setup. But I saw similar code in other
GPU connector classes, we might want to patch them as well.

commits.author: Martin Hickey
commits.message:
[CI/Build] Add publishing to TestPyPi and refactor PyPi publish (#611)

* Add publishing to TestPyPi and refactor PyPi publish

Added publishing to TestPyPi on every PR merge and also
a release. This will give regular intermediatery builds between
releases.

In addition did some refactoring for improvement and security reasons
as follows:

- Separated build from the publish jobs
- Added security action to the runner
- Specified latest action versions to use
- Replaced GH release action with the `gh` CLI command directly
- Replaced `twine` command with pypi publish action

Note: The publishing no longer requires tokens for publishing to PyPi and TestPyPi.
It insteads uses "Trusted Publishers": https://docs.pypi.org/trusted-publishers/creating-a-project-through-oidc/
This reduces the steps for automated publishing in the workflow.

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Add text to describe process for publishing

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

---------

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

commits.author: Martin Hickey
commits.message:
[CI/Build]: Add project metadata to pyproject toml file (#592)

* Add project metadata to pyproject toml

The pyproject.toml file can handle most the project metadata
in a more central location to the `setup.py` file. This commit
moves it to the toml file.

It also adds dynamic versioning which uses git tags.

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Update files after ruff check

* Fix pyproject toml file after rebase

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Add setuptools to requirements

This is neded by the build system as it may use any version
of setuptools whihc may not be compatible.

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Update PR template to remove old tagging information

Now using dynamic versioning, no need anymore to add tags.
This only needs to be done now at release time.

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Update after review

Review comments:

commits.message:
[Bugfix] Update local_backend.py, use thread pool instead of process pool in localdisk backend (#325)

Update local_backend.py, use thread pool instead of process pool

Multi-process won't share memory space, if you simply open a process to save the chunk to file, it will get an unaccessible pointer and stuck. A simple solution is to use threadpool instead. If you want a higher speed, consider build-in multi-thread functions of torch.

commits.author: Tomer Shmilovich
commits.message:
[Core] Support NIXL storage obj backend (#1557)

* [Core] Generalize NixlFilePool

Signed-off-by: Tomer Shmilovich <tshmilovich@nvidia.com>

* [Core] NixlStorageBackend support backend params

Signed-off-by: Tomer Shmilovich <tshmilovich@nvidia.com>

* [Core] Support NixlStorageBackend OBJ backend

Adding support for NIXL obj backend.

in order to use this backend, AWS parameters should be provided via
extra_config.nixl_backend_params in the yaml file, for example:

extra_config:
  enable_nixl_storage: true
  nixl_backend: OBJ
  nixl_pool_size: 64
  nixl_path: /mnt/nixl/cache/
  nixl_backend_params:
    access_key: <your_access_key>
    secret_key: <your_secret_key>
    bucket: <your_bucket>
    region: <your_region>

Signed-off-by: Tomer Shmilovich <tshmilovich@nvidia.com>

* [Docs] Update docs

commits.author: Martin Hickey
commits.message:
[Misc]: Improve the description provided for PRs (#1679)

Improve description provided for PRs

This commit updates the PR template so that it may guide users to
provide more details about the PR being submitted. At the moment, it is
usually just issue number that it fixes.

The value is twofold:

1. Its helps the reviewers understand what the PR does and if needed
2. It help others that find the PR later and understand the reason
behind the changes

It also moves details about identifier prefixes to the contributor guide
which is a more relevant place for them.

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

commits.message:
[BugFix][Testing]: Enable unit tests for GDS backend (#1648)

* Fix the GDS tests to work with the updated GdsBackend class constructor

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Fix unit test issues

This commit fixes the failing tests for the GDS backend.
It also checks for CUDA and Linux as these are backend
requirements.

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Fix GDS backend batched_submit_put_task method to return Futures

The GDS backend batched_submit_put_task method calls the submit_put_task
method to persist memory objects to the backend. The submit_put_task
uses a thread safe co-routine to call backend asynchronous persistence
method. This commit fixes batched_submit_put_task to return the Futures
objects from submit_put_task to the caller.

Unit test test_batched_submit_put_task was failing because the Future objects
were none.

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Enable GDS tests

[Test]: Enable unit tests to run on non-CUDA environment (#1575)

* Enable storage backend unit tests to run as non-CUDA

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Add pytest asyncio dependency for async tests

Tests in tests/v1/storage_backend/test_gds_backend.py were not
being run as they required async library.

This adds the pytest asyncio package which enabkles the tests to be run
by default rather than skipping them.

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Add unit test GitHub workflow for non-CUDA tests

This workflow will run non-CUDA unit tests which can run on the
standard runners which are not GPU enabled.

This could help catch issues prior to the running the full tests
on GPU systems. This could be helpful towards resource savings.

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Pinned memory does not work on non-CUDA systems

Pinned (pageâ€‘locked) memory is a CPUâ€‘side optimization for faster,
asynchronous transfers to a CUDA device. If thereâ€™s no CUDA context or
no allocator registered, PyTorch canâ€™t actually pin the memory, so it complains.

commits.author: Martin Hickey
commits.message:
[Chore]: Remove Python 3.9 as the minimum Python version (#1618)

* Remove Python 3.9 as the minimum Python version

LMCache was built on Python 3.10 and as such has keywords like
match which are not compatible in Python 3.9. We therefore
would need to make changes to the code base. Python 3.9
will no longer be supported next month. Therefore, it is more
practical to support 3.10 as the minimum version.

This is a revert of some of the changes in:
https://github.com/LMCache/LMCache/pull/1440

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Changes required after code quality tools ran

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

---------

commits.author: Isaac K. Ko
commits.message:
[Bugfix][Enhancement] Improve multi-round-qa.py and data_preprocessing.py scripts (#1321)

* multi-round-qa: fix argument name for init_logger

Using the --verbose option causes an error.

In the init_logger function, `level` should be changed to `log_level`,
or omit it as in this patch.

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* multi-round-qa: add an assert for insufficient trace data

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* multi-round-qa: add --dry-run option

This option helps quickly validate trace readability.

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* data_preprocessing: add --model option

This option allows you to specify a different tokenizer. The default
value is still `mistralai/Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.2`.

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* data_preprocessing: adjust estimate_num_tokens location

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* data_preprocessing: exclude invalid conversations

Although there has been some existing logic to exclude invalid
conversations, it is still insufficient.

This patch excludes the following invalid conversations:

- The number of conversations is not even
- The conversation starts with GPT or system
- The conversation ends with human
- GPT or human appears consecutively
- The conversation is too long (may exceed the maximum model length)
- Unknown "from" values

Experimental results using `ShareGPT_V3_unfiltered_cleaned_split.json`
are as follows:

  $ python data_preprocessing.py
  Number of IDs: 94145
  Excluded number of IDs: 58746
  Data to process: 35399

A significant number of traces are excluded.

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* data_preprocessing: use tqdm in loops

The script takes several minutes to run, so it's better to have a
progress bar.

  $ python data_preprocessing.py
  Loading trace file..
  Number of IDs: 94145
  Veryfing trace..
  100%|â–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆ| 94145/94145 [01:28<00:00, 1069.70it/s]
  Excluded Number of IDs: 58746
  Data to Process: 35399
  100%|â–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆ| 35399/35399 [01:06<00:00, 531.55it/s]

`tqdm` is already a dependency of `vLLM` and `LMCache`, so there's no
additional installation required.

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* data_preprocessing: add --trace option

This option allows you to specify a trace file. The default value is
still `ShareGPT_V3_unfiltered_cleaned_split.json`.

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* multi-round-qa: fix QPS print statement to print actual QPS value

The print statement outputs qps (configured value) but not _qps (actual
value):

  print(f"  \033[33mQPS: \033[32m{qps:.4f} reqs/s\033[0m\n")

Fix the print statement to output both configured value and actual value.

Changes:

- Rename config qps (`qps`) to `config_qps`
- Rename actual qps (`_qps`) to `actual_qps`
- Print both `actual_qps` and `config_qps`

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* doc: update README.md for multi-round-qa and data_preprocessing

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

---------

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

commits.author: Martin Hickey
commits.message:
[CI/Build]: Fix Linux CUDA wheel builds (#775)

* Fix linux builds with cibuildwheel

Build is broken because torch 2.7 is not supported by CUDA 12.4 and torch
2.7 does not have distributions for manylinux_2_17_x86_64.

This commit updates the manylinux cuda image used by cibuilder to
manylinux_2_28_x86_64 which is supported by torch 2.7

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Remove cibuild configuration duplication

Configuration for cibuilder was set in pyproject.toml and also as
env variables in GitHub publish workflow.

This commit removes the configuration in workflow and centralizes
it in pyproject.toml.

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Clean more disk space from runner

Running out of space when building cp312-manylinux_x86_64 wheel.
This step is to remove more space.

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Refactor runner disk cleanup

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

---------

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

commits.author: Dan Aloni
commits.message:
[Feat] GdsBackend: allow to pass use_direct_io flag (#862)

GdsBackend: allow to pass use_direct_io flag

This flag allows to benchmark underlying file system performance with
respect to KV cache load/save. When it is being passed, and while cuFile
POSIX fallback is being used, the Linux pagecache does not cache the
file's content.

Signed-off-by: Dan Aloni <dan@kernelim.com>

* [Misc] GdsBackend: add internal fallback to POSIX APIs

In this change a `use_cufile` extra config variable is added to control
whether cuFile APIs will be used by GdsBackend. In addition, based on
fstype we can control the default vault of this variable and can turn
cuFile usage off.

The libcufile APIs are not always successful in implementing the POSIX
compatibility fallback. when either the cuFile own POSIX implementation
is triggered, or when GdsBackend's own POSIX implementation is used,
there expected to be at least one copy of data from main memory to GPU
buffers.

Fixes: #795

Signed-off-by: Dan Aloni <dan@kernelim.com>

* [Misc] GdsBackend: use_cufile - allow case insenstive "true" as input

Signed-off-by: Dan Aloni <dan@kernelim.com>

commits.author: Martin Hickey
commits.message:
[CI/Build] Add publishing to TestPyPi and refactor PyPi publish (#611)

* Add publishing to TestPyPi and refactor PyPi publish

Added publishing to TestPyPi on every PR merge and also
a release. This will give regular intermediatery builds between
releases.

In addition did some refactoring for improvement and security reasons
as follows:

- Separated build from the publish jobs
- Added security action to the runner
- Specified latest action versions to use
- Replaced GH release action with the `gh` CLI command directly
- Replaced `twine` command with pypi publish action

Note: The publishing no longer requires tokens for publishing to PyPi and TestPyPi.
It insteads uses "Trusted Publishers": https://docs.pypi.org/trusted-publishers/creating-a-project-through-oidc/
This reduces the steps for automated publishing in the workflow.

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Add text to describe process for publishing

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

commits.author: Ilya Yanok
commits.message:
Micro benchmark for VLLMPagedMemGPUConnectorV2.toGpu and a performance fix (#678)

* gpu_connector: add VLLMPagedConnectorV2.to_gpu micro-benchmark

We've noticed it spends a lot of time in
VLLMPagedConnectorV2._pointers_are_good, so before trying to improve it,
adding a micro-benchmark.

* pagedMemGPUConnectorV2: optimize to/from GPU

There was a number of issues with `_pointersAreGood` method, causing
it to massively dominate the to/from GPU cost.

First, why even check it, if the check takes linear time at worst, and
the initialization is also linear?

Then, getting/setting elements of a tensor is suboptimal, let's do it
in a single assignment instead.

And finally, the actual multi-layer transfer kernel runs on GPU, so
let's move pointers there.

This gives 3.3x speedup in the microbenchmark, see the results here:
https://gist.github.com/yanok/685182fe15b46bf0d99797853a4f9f9a

I only changed the VLLMPagedMemGPUConnectorV2 class, since that's the
one we are currently using in our setup. But I saw similar code in other
GPU connector classes, we might want to patch them as well.

commits.author: cwwu
commits.message:
[feat] Add configuration logging (#529)

* feat(config): Add configuration logging to LMCache

This commit adds consistent configuration logging functionality to both the main and experimental versions of LMCache.

The new functionality helps with debugging and monitoring by providing a clear view of the active configuration when LMCache is initialized. This is particularly useful in complex deployment scenarios where configuration might come from multiple sources.

commits.author: Xueshen Liu
commits.message:
[Bugfix] Update local_backend.py, use thread pool instead of process pool in localdisk backend (#325)

Update local_backend.py, use thread pool instead of process pool

Multi-process won't share memory space, if you simply open a process to save the chunk to file, it will get an unaccessible pointer and stuck. A simple solution is to use threadpool instead. If you want a higher speed, consider build-in multi-thread functions of torch.

commits.author: Tomer Shmilovich
commits.message:
[Core] Support NIXL storage obj backend (#1557)

* [Core] Generalize NixlFilePool

Signed-off-by: Tomer Shmilovich <tshmilovich@nvidia.com>

* [Core] NixlStorageBackend support backend params

Signed-off-by: Tomer Shmilovich <tshmilovich@nvidia.com>

* [Core] Support NixlStorageBackend OBJ backend

Adding support for NIXL obj backend.

in order to use this backend, AWS parameters should be provided via
extra_config.nixl_backend_params in the yaml file, for example:

extra_config:
  enable_nixl_storage: true
  nixl_backend: OBJ
  nixl_pool_size: 64
  nixl_path: /mnt/nixl/cache/
  nixl_backend_params:
    access_key: <your_access_key>
    secret_key: <your_secret_key>
    bucket: <your_bucket>
    region: <your_region>

Signed-off-by: Tomer Shmilovich <tshmilovich@nvidia.com>

* [Docs] Update docs

Signed-off-by: Tomer Shmilovich <tshmilovich@nvidia.com>

---------

Signed-off-by: Tomer Shmilovich <tshmilovich@nvidia.com>

commits.author: Martin Hickey
commits.message:
[Misc]: Improve the description provided for PRs (#1679)

Improve description provided for PRs

This commit updates the PR template so that it may guide users to
provide more details about the PR being submitted. At the moment, it is
usually just issue number that it fixes.

The value is twofold:

1. Its helps the reviewers understand what the PR does and if needed
2. It help others that find the PR later and understand the reason
behind the changes

It also moves details about identifier prefixes to the contributor guide
which is a more relevant place for them.

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

[BugFix][Testing]: Enable unit tests for GDS backend (#1648)

* Fix the GDS tests to work with the updated GdsBackend class constructor

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Fix unit test issues

This commit fixes the failing tests for the GDS backend.
It also checks for CUDA and Linux as these are backend
requirements.

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Fix GDS backend batched_submit_put_task method to return Futures

The GDS backend batched_submit_put_task method calls the submit_put_task
method to persist memory objects to the backend. The submit_put_task
uses a thread safe co-routine to call backend asynchronous persistence
method. This commit fixes batched_submit_put_task to return the Futures
objects from submit_put_task to the caller.

Unit test test_batched_submit_put_task was failing because the Future objects
were none.

commits.author: Martin Hickey
commits.message:
[Chore]: Remove Python 3.9 as the minimum Python version (#1618)

* Remove Python 3.9 as the minimum Python version

LMCache was built on Python 3.10 and as such has keywords like
match which are not compatible in Python 3.9. We therefore
would need to make changes to the code base. Python 3.9
will no longer be supported next month. Therefore, it is more
practical to support 3.10 as the minimum version.

This is a revert of some of the changes in:
https://github.com/LMCache/LMCache/pull/1440

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

commits.author: Isaac K. Ko
commits.message:
[Bugfix][Enhancement] Improve multi-round-qa.py and data_preprocessing.py scripts (#1321)

* multi-round-qa: fix argument name for init_logger

Using the --verbose option causes an error.

In the init_logger function, `level` should be changed to `log_level`,
or omit it as in this patch.

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* multi-round-qa: add an assert for insufficient trace data

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* multi-round-qa: add --dry-run option

This option helps quickly validate trace readability.

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* data_preprocessing: add --model option

This option allows you to specify a different tokenizer. The default
value is still `mistralai/Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.2`.

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* data_preprocessing: adjust estimate_num_tokens location

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* data_preprocessing: exclude invalid conversations

Although there has been some existing logic to exclude invalid
conversations, it is still insufficient.

This patch excludes the following invalid conversations:

- The number of conversations is not even
- The conversation starts with GPT or system
- The conversation ends with human
- GPT or human appears consecutively
- The conversation is too long (may exceed the maximum model length)
- Unknown "from" values

Experimental results using `ShareGPT_V3_unfiltered_cleaned_split.json`
are as follows:

  $ python data_preprocessing.py
  Number of IDs: 94145
  Excluded number of IDs: 58746
  Data to process: 35399

A significant number of traces are excluded.

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* data_preprocessing: use tqdm in loops

The script takes several minutes to run, so it's better to have a
progress bar.

  $ python data_preprocessing.py
  Loading trace file..
  Number of IDs: 94145
  Veryfing trace..
  100%|â–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆ| 94145/94145 [01:28<00:00, 1069.70it/s]
  Excluded Number of IDs: 58746
  Data to Process: 35399
  100%|â–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆ| 35399/35399 [01:06<00:00, 531.55it/s]

`tqdm` is already a dependency of `vLLM` and `LMCache`, so there's no
additional installation required.

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* data_preprocessing: add --trace option

This option allows you to specify a trace file. The default value is
still `ShareGPT_V3_unfiltered_cleaned_split.json`.

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* multi-round-qa: fix QPS print statement to print actual QPS value

The print statement outputs qps (configured value) but not _qps (actual
value):

  print(f"  \033[33mQPS: \033[32m{qps:.4f} reqs/s\033[0m\n")

Fix the print statement to output both configured value and actual value.

Changes:

- Rename config qps (`qps`) to `config_qps`
- Rename actual qps (`_qps`) to `actual_qps`
- Print both `actual_qps` and `config_qps`

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

* doc: update README.md for multi-round-qa and data_preprocessing

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

---------

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

commits.author: Isaac K. Ko
commits.message:
[Bugfix] Close file descriptor when using use_odirect feature (#1264)

Fix file descriptor leak in use_odirect feature

- In async_save_bytes_to_disk(), explicitly close the file descriptor
- In async_load_bytes_from_disk() and load_bytes_from_disk(), ensure
  file descriptors are closed through the use of `with` statements,
  which internally close the fd via fdo.close()

Signed-off-by: Kwangjin Ko <kwangjin.ko@sk.com>

[CI/Build]: Fix Linux CUDA wheel builds (#775)

* Fix linux builds with cibuildwheel

Build is broken because torch 2.7 is not supported by CUDA 12.4 and torch
2.7 does not have distributions for manylinux_2_17_x86_64.

This commit updates the manylinux cuda image used by cibuilder to
manylinux_2_28_x86_64 which is supported by torch 2.7

Signed-off-by: Martin Hickey <martin.hickey@ie.ibm.com>

* Remove cibuild configuration duplication

Configuration for cibuilder was set in pyproject.toml and also as
env variables in GitHub publish workflow.

This commit removes the configuration in workflow and centralizes
it in pyproject.toml.

Running out of space when building cp312-manylinux_x86_64 wheel.
This step is to remove more space.

commits.author: Dan Aloni
commits.message:
[Feat] GdsBackend: allow to pass use_direct_io flag (#862)

GdsBackend: allow to pass use_direct_io flag

This flag allows to benchmark underlying file system performance with
respect to KV cache load/save. When it is being passed, and while cuFile
POSIX fallback is being used, the Linux pagecache does not cache the
file's content.

Signed-off-by: Dan Aloni <dan@kernelim.com>

commits.author: Dan Aloni
commits.message:
[Misc] GdsBackend: add internal fallback to POSIX APIs (#811)

* [Misc] GdsBackend: add internal fallback to POSIX APIs

In this change a `use_cufile` extra config variable is added to control
whether cuFile APIs will be used by GdsBackend. In addition, based on
fstype we can control the default vault of this variable and can turn
cuFile usage off.

The libcufile APIs are not always successful in implementing the POSIX
compatibility fallback. when either the cuFile own POSIX implementation
is triggered, or when GdsBackend's own POSIX implementation is used,
there expected to be at least one copy of data from main memory to GPU
buffers.

Fixes: #795

Signed-off-by: Dan Aloni <dan@kernelim.com>

* [Misc] GdsBackend: use_cufile - allow case insenstive "true" as input

Signed-off-by: Dan Aloni <dan@kernelim.com>

commits.author: Ilya Yanok
commits.message:
Micro benchmark for VLLMPagedMemGPUConnectorV2.toGpu and a performance fix (#678)

* gpu_connector: add VLLMPagedConnectorV2.to_gpu micro-benchmark

We've noticed it spends a lot of time in
VLLMPagedConnectorV2._pointers_are_good, so before trying to improve it,
adding a micro-benchmark.

* pagedMemGPUConnectorV2: optimize to/from GPU

There was a number of issues with `_pointersAreGood` method, causing
it to massively dominate the to/from GPU cost.

First, why even check it, if the check takes linear time at worst, and
the initialization is also linear?

Then, getting/setting elements of a tensor is suboptimal, let's do it
in a single assignment instead.

And finally, the actual multi-layer transfer kernel runs on GPU, so
let's move pointers there.

This gives 3.3x speedup in the microbenchmark, see the results here:
https://gist.github.com/yanok/685182fe15b46bf0d99797853a4f9f9a

I only changed the VLLMPagedMemGPUConnectorV2 class, since that's the
one we are currently using in our setup. But I saw similar code in other
GPU connector classes, we might want to patch them as well.

commits.message:
[Bugfix] Update local_backend.py, use thread pool instead of process pool in localdisk backend (#325)

Update local_backend.py, use thread pool instead of process pool

Multi-process won't share memory space, if you simply open a process to save the chunk to file, it will get an unaccessible pointer and stuck. A simple solution is to use threadpool instead. If you want a higher speed, consider build-in multi-thread functions of torch.
